   "id": "6bd4dc3a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Influence functions for data mislabeling\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, we will take a closer look at the theory of influence functions with the help of a synthetic dataset. Data mislabeling occurs whenever some examples from a usually big dataset are wrongly-labeled. In real-life this happens fairly often, e.g. as a consequence of human error, or noise in the data. \n",
    "\n",
    "Let's consider a classification problem with the following notation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "x_i &\\in \\mathbb{R}^d \\\\\n",
    "y_i &\\in \\{0, 1\\} \\\\\n",
    "\\forall i &\\in [ N ]\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "In other words, we have a dataset containing $N$ samples, each with label 1 or 0. As typical example you can think of y indicating whether a patient has a disease based on some feature representation $x$. \n",
    "\n",
    "Let's now introduce a toy model that will help us delve into the theory and practical utility of influence functions. We will assume that $y$ is a Bernoulli binary random variable while the input $x$ is d-dimensional Gaussian distribution which depends on the label $y$. More precisely:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_i \\sim \\text{Ber}\\left (0.5 \\right) \\\\\n",
    "x_i \\sim \\mathcal{N}\\left ((1 - y_i) \\mu_1 + y_i \\mu_2, \\sigma^2 I \\right),\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with fixed means and diagonal covariance. Implementing the sampling scheme in python is straightforward and can be achieved by first sampling $y$ and afterward $x$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6623665f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The following code snippet generates the aforementioned dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "23cb0e79",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from valuation.influence.model_wrappers import TorchBinaryLogisticRegression\n",
    "import torch\n",
    "import torch.nn.functional as F\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from torch.optim import AdamW, lr_scheduler\n",
    "from valuation.utils.dataset import synthetic_classification_dataset\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay\n",
    "from valuation.utils.plotting import plot_dataset, plot_influences\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "num_samples = 10000\n",
    "num_features = 2\n",
    "sigma = 0.2\n",
    "means = np.asarray([[0.0, 0.0], [1.0, 1.0]])\n",
    "\n",
    "num_classes = len(means)\n",
    "train_ds, val_ds, test_ds = synthetic_classification_dataset(\n",
    "    means, sigma, num_samples, train_size=0.7, test_size=0.2\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ebc8a087",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Given the simplicity of the dataset, we can calculate exactly the optimal decision boundary(that which maximizes our accuracy). The following code maps a continuous line of z values to a 2-dimensional vector in feature space (More details are in the appendix to this notebook.)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "c8b0dd43",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from valuation.utils.dataset import decision_boundary_fixed_variance_2d\n",
    "\n",
    "decision_boundary_fn = decision_boundary_fixed_variance_2d(means[0], means[1])\n",
    "decision_boundary = decision_boundary_fn(np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, 100))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ec223a74",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Plotting the dataset\n",
    "Let's plot the dataset is plotted with their respective labels and the optimal decision line"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "788f77d2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x576 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "datasets = {\n",
    "    \"train\": train_ds,\n",
    "    \"test\": test_ds,\n",
    "}\n",
    "x_min = np.asarray([-2, -2])\n",
    "x_max = np.asarray([3, 3])\n",
    "plot_dataset(\n",
    "    train_ds,\n",
    "    test_ds,\n",
    "    xlabel=\"$x_0$\",\n",
    "    ylabel=\"$x_1$\",\n",
    "    legend_title=\"$y - labels$\",\n",
    "    line=decision_boundary,\n",
    "    s=10,\n",
    "    suptitle=\"Plot of train-test data\",\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dce9b1d3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that there are samples which go across the optimal decision boundary and will be wrongly labelled. The optimal decision boundary can not discriminate these as the mislabelling is a consequence of the presence of random noise."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3d6bbcac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Training the model\n",
    "\n",
    "We will now train a logistic regression model on the train data. This can be done with the following"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "bdef13ee",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model = TorchBinaryLogisticRegression(num_features)\n",
    "device = torch.device(\"cuda:0\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\")\n",
    "model.to(device)\n",
    "\n",
    "num_epochs = 50\n",
    "lr = 0.05\n",
    "weight_decay = 0.05\n",
    "batch_size = 128\n",
    "\n",
    "optimizer = AdamW(params=model.parameters(), lr=lr, weight_decay=weight_decay)\n",
    "scheduler = lr_scheduler.CosineAnnealingLR(optimizer, T_max=num_epochs)\n",
    "train_loss, val_loss = model.fit(\n",
    "    x_train=train_ds[0],\n",
    "    y_train=train_ds[1].astype(float),\n",
    "    x_val=val_ds[0],\n",
    "    y_val=val_ds[1].astype(float),\n",
    "    loss=F.binary_cross_entropy,\n",
    "    optimizer=optimizer,\n",
    "    scheduler=scheduler,\n",
    "    num_epochs=num_epochs,\n",
    "    batch_size=batch_size,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1b424023",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And let's check that the model is not overfitting"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "id": "22d3225c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x504 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))\n",
    "plt.plot(train_loss, label=\"train\")\n",
    "plt.plot(val_loss, label=\"val\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "779b9394",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A look at the confusion matrix also shows good results"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "d6fcf1cc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<sklearn.metrics._plot.confusion_matrix.ConfusionMatrixDisplay at 0x7f8e5d2e56f0>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 20,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pred_probabilities = model(test_ds[0]).detach()\n",
    "pred_y_test = [1 if prob > 0.5 else 0 for prob in pred_probabilities]\n",
    "\n",
    "cm = confusion_matrix(test_ds[1], pred_y_test)\n",
    "disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm)\n",
    "disp.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ab0b0cf8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Calculating influences"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "416eb518",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is important that the model converges to a point near the optimum, since the influence values assume that we are at a minimum (or close) in the loss landscape. The function\n",
    "\n",
    "$$I(x_1, y_1, x_2, y_2) \\colon \\mathbb{R}^d \\times \\mathbb{R}^d \\to \\mathbb{R}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "measures the influence of the data point $x_1$ onto $x_2$ conditioned on the training targets $y_1$ and $y_2$ trough some model parameters $\\theta$. If the loss function L is differentiable, we can take $I$ to be\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "I(x_1, x_2) = \\nabla_\\theta\\; L(x_1, y_1) ^\\mathsf{T} \\; H_\\theta^{-1} \\; \\nabla_\\theta \\; L(x_2, y_2)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "See [\"Understanding Black-box Predictions via Influence Functions\"](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1703.04730.pdf) for a detailed derivation of this formula"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "62564ecc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's take a subset of the training data points, which we will calculate the influence values of. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "id": "22c958ed",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x = train_ds[0][:100]\n",
    "y = train_ds[1][:100]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0bc2b6ff",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In pyDVL, the influence of the training points on the test points can be calculated with the following"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "id": "f817a6c3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from valuation.influence.general import influences\n",
    "\n",
    "influence_values = influences(\n",
    "    model=model,\n",
    "    loss=F.binary_cross_entropy,\n",
    "    x_train=x,\n",
    "    y_train=y.astype(float),\n",
    "    x_test=test_ds[0],\n",
    "    y_test=test_ds[1].astype(float),\n",
    "    influence_type=\"up\",\n",
    "    inversion_method=\"direct\",  # use 'cg' for big models\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d1e98dc2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The above explicitly constructs the Hessian. This can often be computationally expensive and conjugate gradient approximate calculation should be used for bigger models. \n",
    "\n",
    "With the influence type 'up', train influences have shape [NxM] where N is the number of test samples and M is the number of training samples. They therefore associate to each training sample its influence on each test sample. \n",
    "Influence type 'perturbation', instead, return an array of shape  [NxMxF], where F is the number of features in input, ie. the length of x. \n",
    "\n",
    "In our case, in order to have a value of the total average influence of a point we can just average across training samples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "id": "f3d186c5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "mean_train_influences = np.mean(influence_values, axis=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f22020de",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's plot the results"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "id": "dd568ba5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x576 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plot_influences(\n",
    "    x,\n",
    "    mean_train_influences,\n",
    "    line=decision_boundary,\n",
    "    xlabel=\"$x_0$\",\n",
    "    ylabel=\"$x_1$\",\n",
    "    suptitle=\"Influences of input points\",\n",
    "    legend_title=\"influence values\",\n",
    "    colorbar_limits=(-0.3,),\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2d262071",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can see that, as we approach the separation line, the influences tend to move away from zero, i.e. the points become more decisive for model training, some in a positive way, some negative."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8989f90c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As a further test, let's introduce some labelling errors into $y$ and see how the distribution of the influences changes. Let's flip the first 10 labels and calculate influences"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "id": "643977a7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "y_corrupted = np.copy(y)\n",
    "y_corrupted[:10] = [1 - yi for yi in y[:10]]\n",
    "\n",
    "influence_values = influences(\n",
    "    model=model,\n",
    "    loss=F.binary_cross_entropy,\n",
    "    x_train=x,\n",
    "    y_train=y_corrupted.astype(float),\n",
    "    x_test=test_ds[0],\n",
    "    y_test=test_ds[1].astype(float),\n",
    "    influence_type=\"up\",\n",
    "    inversion_method=\"direct\",  # use 'cg' for big models\n",
    ")\n",
    "mean_train_influences = np.mean(influence_values, axis=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "id": "2a7d59b8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Average mislabelled data influence: -0.4771455733701123\n",
      "Average correct data influence: 0.004410349344254106\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Average mislabelled data influence:\", np.mean(mean_train_influences[:10]))\n",
    "print(\"Average correct data influence:\", np.mean(mean_train_influences[10:]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "id": "e95ca0e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x576 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plot_influences(\n",
    "    x,\n",
    "    mean_train_influences,\n",
    "    corrupted_indices=np.array(range(10)),\n",
    "    line=decision_boundary,\n",
    "    xlabel=\"$x_0$\",\n",
    "    ylabel=\"$x_1$\",\n",
    "    suptitle=\"Influences of input points with corrupted data\",\n",
    "    legend_title=\"influence values\",\n",
    "    colorbar_limits=(-0.3,),\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "80f76c03",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Red circles indicate the points which have been corrupted. We can see that the mislabelled data have a more negative average influence on the model, especially those that are farther away from the decision boundary."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bfcbebd9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Appendix: Calculating the decision boundary\n",
    "\n",
    "For obtaining the optimal discriminator one has to solve the equation\n",
    "\n",
    "$$p(x|y=0)=p(x|y=1)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and determine the solution set $X$. Let's take the following probabilities\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "p(x|y=0)&=\\mathcal{N}\\left (\\mu_1, \\sigma^2 I \\right) \\\\\n",
    "p(x|y=1)&=\\mathcal{N}\\left (\\mu_2, \\sigma^2 I \\right)\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For a single fixed diagonal variance parameterized by $\\sigma$, the optimal discriminator lays at points which are equidistant from the means of the two distributions, i.e.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\| x - \\mu_1 \\|^2 &= \\| x - \\mu_2 \\|^2 \\\\\n",
    "\\| \\mu_1 \\|^2 -2 x^\\mathsf{T} \\mu_1 &= \\| \\mu_2 \\|^2 -2 x^\\mathsf{T} \\mu_2 \\\\\n",
    "\\implies 0 &= 2 (\\mu_2 - \\mu_1)^\\mathsf{T} x + \\| \\mu_1 \\|^2 - \\| \\mu_2 \\|^2 \\\\\n",
    "0 &= \\mu_1^\\mathsf{T}x - \\mu_2^\\mathsf{T}x - \\frac{1}{2} \\mu_1^\\mathsf{T} \\mu_1 + \\frac{1}{2} \\mu_2^\\mathsf{T} \\mu_2\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is just the implicit description of the line. Solving for the explicit form can be achieved by enforcing a functional form $f(z) = x = a z + b$ with $z \\in \\mathbb{R}$ onto $x$. After the term is inserted in the previous equation\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "0 = (\\mu_2 - \\mu_1)^\\mathsf{T} (az + b) + \\frac{1}{2} \\| \\mu_1 \\|^2 - \\| \\mu_2 \\|^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We can write $a$ since, by symmetry, it is expected to be explicitly orthogonal to $\\mu_2 - \\mu_1$. Then, solving for $b$, the solution can be found to be\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "f(z) = \\underbrace{\\begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\\\ -1 & 0 \\end{bmatrix} (\\mu_2 - \\mu_1)}_a z + \\underbrace{\\frac{\\mu_1 + \\mu_2}{2}}_b\n",
    "$$"
   ]
  }
 ],
